The function leaks memory because you allocate a new `Order` on the heap but never delete or transfer ownership of it after processing. To fix this, you need to ensure that whoever calls `processOrder` is responsible for freeing the memory, often achieved by reopening the order to the function using `std::unique_ptr`. Here is the corrected version:

```cpp
#include <memory>

void processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {
    if (order->isValid()) {
        // logic for high freq execution
        executeTrade(order);
    }
    // Memory is automatically freed at the end of the scope
}

// in the main loop
auto newOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(data);
processOrder(std::move(newOrder));
```
